# 6. Template Literals

## Definition

Template Literals are a modern feature introduced in **ES6 (ECMAScript 2015)**. They use **backticks (` `)** instead of quotation marks and allow variables
and expressions to be embedded directly into strings using **${ }**.

Template literals make string creation easier, more readable, and more maintainable than traditional string concatenation.

---

## Features

### String Interpolation

Variables can be inserted directly into strings.

```javascript
let name = "Ritika";
console.log(`Hello ${name}`);
```

---

### Expression Evaluation

Mathematical expressions can be evaluated inside `${}`.

```javascript
let a = 10;
let b = 20;

console.log(`${a+b}`);
```

---

### Multi-line Strings

Template literals support multi-line text without using `\n`.

```javascript
let msg = `Welcome
to
JavaScript`;
```

---

### Function Calls

Functions can also be called inside template literals.

```javascript
function greet(name){
   return `Hello ${name}`;
}

console.log(`${greet("Ritika")}`);
```

---

## Advantages

* Cleaner syntax.
* Better readability.
* Supports multi-line strings.
* Simplifies string concatenation.
* Allows embedding expressions and function calls.

---

